Linear regression

Simple linear regression

Estimation

gm2007 <- gapminder %>% filter(year == 2007)
model_lm <- lm(lifeExp ~ gdpPercap, data = gm2007)
model_lm
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = lifeExp ~ gdpPercap, data = gm2007)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)    gdpPercap  
##   5.957e+01    6.371e-04

Demo dplyr::summarise function

  • Slope = cor(x,y) * sd(y) / sd(x)
  • Regression line passes through (mean(x), mean(y))
gm2007 %>%
  summarize(cor_xy = cor(gdpPercap, lifeExp),
            sd_x = sd(gdpPercap),
            sd_y = sd(lifeExp),
            xbar = mean(gdpPercap),
            ybar = mean(lifeExp),
            hat_beta1 = cor_xy * sd_y / sd_x,
            hat_beta0 = ybar - hat_beta1 * xbar)
## # A tibble: 1 x 7
##   cor_xy   sd_x  sd_y   xbar  ybar hat_beta1 hat_beta0
##    <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1  0.679 12860.  12.1 11680.  67.0  0.000637      59.6

(ISLR 3.8):

se(beta hat) = sigma / sqrt(sum((x - mean(x))^2))

Estimated by:

se(beta hat) = sigma hat / sqrt(sum((x - mean(x))^2))

where (ISLR 3.15):

sigma hat = RSE = sqrt( RSS / (n-2) )

augment(model_lm) %>%
  summarize(RSS = sum(.resid^2),
            RSE = sqrt(RSS / (n() - 2)),
            std.error = RSE / sqrt(sum( (gdpPercap - mean(gdpPercap))^2 ))  )
## # A tibble: 1 x 3
##      RSS   RSE std.error
##    <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 11086.  8.90 0.0000583

“Portion of variance in outcome explained by simple linear regression model”

\[ R^2 = \text{cor}(x,y)^2 \]

cor(gm2007$gdpPercap, gm2007$lifeExp)^2
## [1] 0.4605827

\[ R^2 = 1 - \frac{\text{RSS}}{\text{TSS}} \]

augment(model_lm) %>%
  summarize(RSS = sum(.resid^2),
            TSS = sum( (lifeExp - mean(lifeExp))^2),
            R2 = 1 - RSS/TSS)
## # A tibble: 1 x 3
##      RSS    TSS    R2
##    <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 11086. 20552. 0.461

Diagnostic plots

Idea: look for patterns in residuals, which could indicate systemic error (bias)

augment(model_lm) %>%
  ggplot(aes(gdpPercap, .resid)) +
  geom_point()

Other diagnostics:

  • Checking for (approximate) normality with quantile-quantile plot
  • Checking for influential observations

Cook’s distance, cooksd in the plots, measures how much the predictions for all other observations change if we leave out one observation

Point with high cooksd values

plot(model_lm)
